  "prompt": "What is the temperature on the planet Mercury at the demarcation point between light and dark?",
  "response": "Mercury is the closest planet to the Sun and experiences extreme temperature variations due to its very thin atmosphere, which cannot retain heat. On Mercury:\n\n- **Day Side:** Temperatures can soar up to approximately **430\u202f\u00b0C (800\u202fK)**.\n- **Night Side:** Temperatures can plummet to around **-180\u202f\u00b0C (93\u202fK)**.\n\n**At the Terminator (the demarcation line between the light and dark sides):**\n\nThe temperature is intermediate between the scorching day side and the frigid night side. Estimates based on thermal models and data from missions like NASA's MESSENGER suggest that the temperature at Mercury's terminator typically hovers around **350\u202fK (\u224877\u202f\u00b0C)**. This value represents a balance between the intense solar heating and the rapid cooling that occurs without a substantial atmosphere to mediate temperature changes.\n\n**Key Points:**\n- **Extreme Temperature Fluctuations:** Mercury has the most significant temperature range of all the planets in our Solar System.\n- **No Substantial Atmosphere:** This contributes to the rapid heating and cooling, especially noticeable at the terminator.\n- **Terminator Temperature Estimate:** Approximately **350\u202fK (77\u00b0C)**, though exact temperatures can vary based on specific conditions and surface properties.\n\nUnderstanding Mercury's temperature dynamics is crucial for missions aiming to study its surface and geological history, as well as for designing spacecraft that can withstand its harsh thermal environment.",
